\cb3 The beauty of this is that the Loader only runs once at the start. After it connects the ports, it steps out of the way, and the nodes communicate directly.\cb1 \
\
\cb3 1. The JSON-DSL Structure\cb1 \
\cb3 We define the "nodes" (the agents) and the "links" (the edges).\cb1 \
\
\cb3 JSON\cb1 \
\cb3 \{\cb1 \
\cb3   "name": "Sales Lead LUW",\cb1 \
\cb3   "nodes": [\cb1 \
\cb3     \{ "id": "INGEST", "class": "LeadIngestor", "type": "text" \},\cb1 \
\cb3     \{ "id": "SENTIMENT", "class": "SentimentNode", "type": "object" \},\cb1 \
\cb3     \{ "id": "STRATEGY", "class": "OpusNode", "type": "text" \}\cb1 \
\cb3   ],\cb1 \
\cb3   "links": [\cb1 \
\cb3     \{ "from": "INGEST", "to": "SENTIMENT" \},\cb1 \
\cb3     \{ "from": "SENTIMENT", "to": "STRATEGY" \}\cb1 \
\cb3   ]\cb1 \
\cb3 \}\cb1 \
\cb3 2. The Graph Loader (engine.js)\cb1 \
\cb3 This script acts as the "Electrician." It reads the blueprint, creates the nodes, and uses MessageChannel to bridge them.\cb1 \
\
\cb3 JavaScript\cb1 \
\cb3 import \{ MessageChannel \} from 'worker_threads';\cb1 \
\
\cb3 class GraphEngine \{\cb1 \
\cb3     constructor(blueprint, registry) \{\cb1 \
\cb3         this.blueprint = blueprint;\cb1 \
\cb3         this.registry = registry; // A map of class names to actual Classes\cb1 \
\cb3         this.instances = \{\};\cb1 \
\cb3     \}\cb1 \
\
\cb3     assemble() \{\cb1 \
\cb3         // 1. Instantiate all nodes\cb1 \
\cb3         this.blueprint.nodes.forEach(config => \{\cb1 \
\cb3             const NodeClass = this.registry[config.class];\cb1 \
\cb3             this.instances[config.id] = new NodeClass(config.id, config.type);\cb1 \
\cb3         \});\cb1 \
\
\cb3         // 2. Wire them up with MessageChannels\cb1 \
\cb3         this.blueprint.links.forEach(link => \{\cb1 \
\cb3             const nodeA = this.instances[link.from];\cb1 \
\cb3             const nodeB = this.instances[link.to];\cb1 \
\
\cb3             const \{ port1, port2 \} = new MessageChannel();\cb1 \
\
\cb3             // Node A writes to port1\cb1 \
\cb3             nodeA.connectOutput(port1);\cb1 \
\
\cb3             // Node B reads from port2\cb1 \
\cb3             nodeB.connectInput(port2);\cb1 \
\
\cb3             console.log(`[Engine] Wired $\{link.from\} \uc0\u10132  $\{link.to\}`);\cb1 \
\cb3         \});\cb1 \
\cb3     \}\cb1 \
\
\cb3     start(initialData) \{\cb1 \
\cb3         // Find the first node in the blueprint and kick it off\cb1 \
\cb3         const firstNodeId = this.blueprint.nodes[0].id;\cb1 \
\cb3         this.instances[firstNodeId].inputPort.postMessage(initialData);\cb1 \
\cb3     \}\cb1 \
\cb3 \}\cb1 \
\cb3 3. The "Base Agent" Class\cb1 \
\cb3 Every node needs to know how to hold its ports.\cb1 \
\
\cb3 JavaScript\cb1 \
\cb3 class BaseAgent \{\cb1 \
\cb3     constructor(id, outputType) \{\cb1 \
\cb3         this.id = id;\cb1 \
\cb3         this.outputType = outputType;\cb1 \
\cb3         this.inputPort = null;\cb1 \
\cb3         this.outputPort = null;\cb1 \
\cb3     \}\cb1 \
\
\cb3     connectInput(port) \{\cb1 \
\cb3         this.inputPort = port;\cb1 \
\cb3         this.inputPort.on('message', async (data) => \{\cb1 \
\cb3             const result = await this.work(data);\cb1 \
\cb3             if (this.outputPort) this.outputPort.postMessage(result);\cb1 \
\cb3         \});\cb1 \
\cb3     \}\cb1 \
\
\cb3     connectOutput(port) \{\cb1 \
\cb3         this.outputPort = port;\cb1 \
\cb3     \}\cb1 \
\
\cb3     async work(data) \{\cb1 \
\cb3         return data; // Override this in specialized nodes\cb1 \
\cb3     \}\cb1 \
\cb3 \}\cb1 \
\cb3 4. Why this works for your M4 Mac Mini\cb1 \
\cb3 Choreography over Orchestration: Once start() is called, the GraphEngine could literally be deleted from memory. The data is now flowing port-to-port via the Node.js event loop.\cb1 \
\
\cb3 Visualizable: Because you have a JSON DSL, you can send that exact same JSON to your Browser Dashboard. The dashboard can use a library like Cytoscape.js or React Flow to draw the map.\cb1 \
\
\cb3 Observability: You can add a "Special" link that taps into every port and sends a copy of the data to your PHP gateway. This lets you watch the "Pinball" move through the machine in real-time.\cb1 \
\
