\f0\b0\fs31\fsmilli15750 \AppleTypeServices \cf4 \cb5 \strokec4 The role is clearer than it feels, and you're right to want a design step. The trap is that the design method and the framework live at 
\f2\b different layers
\f0\b0 , and conflating them is what makes the role feel murky.\cb1 \
\
\cb5 (I'll engage with the method as you described it \'97 stepwise, event-clustered, data-on-events, actor-on-execution \'97 which puts it in the Event Modeling / Event Storming family regardless of the exact name.)\cb1 \
\
\cb5 ## Two layers, not one\cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf4 \cb5 Event-driven design designs the business.
\f0\b0  Outputs: a catalog of processes, the events that trigger and complete them, the data each event carries, who's authorized to fire them.\cb1 \
\

\f2\b \cb5 The dataflow framework designs the runtime.
\f0\b0  Outputs: how a single process is physically executed \'97 which nodes, which edges, which codecs, which LLM calls, what gets retried.\cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \cb5 These don't compete. The design method produces the inputs that the framework consumes.\cb1 \
\
\cb5 ## The mapping\cb1 \
\
\cb5 | Event-design concept | Framework concept |\cb1 \
\cb5 |---|---|\cb1 \
\cb5 | Process (event cluster) | LUW \'97 one blueprint |\cb1 \
\cb5 | Triggering event / command | LUW input (the plunger) |\cb1 \
\cb5 | Terminal event (fact produced) | LUW output |\cb1 \
\cb5 | Event payload | Typed port schemas \'97 the messages flowing on edges |\cb1 \
\cb5 | Actor / role | Authorization at the LUW boundary |\cb1 \
\cb5 | Intermediate "event" | 
\f2\b Usually a node output, NOT a business event
\f0\b0  |\cb1 \
\
\cb5 ## The trap to avoid\cb1 \
\
\cb5 The natural temptation is: every event becomes a node. Don't. Most node-to-node messages inside a LUW are implementation detail, not business events. If you elevate them, your domain model explodes and you've built a distributed system where you needed a function.\cb1 \
\
\cb5 Rule of thumb: a business event is something a non-technical stakeholder would recognize and care about. *"Lead scored as hot"* is an event. *"Sentiment codec emitted chunk"* is not. The first belongs in the design model; the second is invisible to it.\cb1 \
\
\cb5 ## Where the design method directly feeds the framework\cb1 \
\
\cb5 1. 
\f2\b The LUW catalog.
\f0\b0  Each clustered process becomes one JSON blueprint. This answers "which graphs do I actually need?"\cb1 \
\cb5 2. 
\f2\b The canonical type vocabulary.
\f0\b0  Event payloads become your typed ports: `Lead`, `AuditFinding`, `LogBundle`. This is where the abstract "what types do edges carry?" question gets concrete answers grounded in the domain.\cb1 \
\cb5 3. 
\f2\b Authorization seams.
\f0\b0  Actors \uc0\u8594  who can trigger which LUW. Almost always the boundary is enough; internal nodes don't need separate auth.\cb1 \
\cb5 4. 
\f2\b Decision points.
\f0\b0  Events that require human judgment in the design = where LLM nodes go. Events that are pure derivation = pure nodes. The design method literally tells you where the brains belong.\cb1 \
\cb5 5. 
\f2\b The "done" criterion.
\f0\b0  A LUW is finished when its terminal event is emitted. You now know what success looks like before writing code.\cb1 \
\
\cb5 ## What I'd actually do\cb1 \
\
\cb5 Don't use event-driven design to design the framework. Use it to design 
\f2\b one real LUW
\f0\b0 , and let that force the framework's shape.\cb1 \
\
\cb5 Take Performance Audit *or* Sales Lead. Run the method on just that one:\cb1 \
\
\cb5 - List events (LeadReceived \uc0\u8594  SentimentScored \u8594  ObjectionIdentified \u8594  StrategyDrafted \u8594  LeadUpdated)\cb1 \
\cb5 - Cluster into the process\cb1 \
\cb5 - Attach data to each event\cb1 \
\cb5 - Attach actor to each\cb1 \
\
\cb5 Then ask three questions of every event:\cb1 \
\
\cb5 1. Is this a LUW boundary (input/output) or internal?\cb1 \
\cb5 2. What's the schema of the data it carries? (This is a port type.)\cb1 \
\cb5 3. Is the transition to the next event mechanical, statistical, or judgmental? (Mechanical = pure node. Statistical = small local model. Judgmental = LLM node.)\cb1 \
\
\cb5 You'll exit with: one blueprint, ~5 typed schemas, 1\'962 LLM-node specs, an authorization rule, and a clear "done" event. That's enough to build a v1 framework 
\f2\b against a real process
\f0\b0  instead of in the abstract.\cb1 \
\
\cb5 ## The honest punchline\cb1 \
\
\cb5 The design method's role here is to 
\f2\b stop you from building a framework in search of a problem
\f0\b0 . The conversation so far has been pleasant architecture with no concrete process anchoring it. The minute you run the method on one real LUW, half the framework decisions (port types, error handling, observability needs, LLM placement) will answer themselves because the domain will demand specific answers.\cb1 \
\
\cb5 So the order is: design *the first process* \uc0\u8594  derive the framework requirements from it \u8594  build the smallest framework that satisfies them \u8594  run that process on it \u8594  design the second process \u8594  see what the framework is missing \u8594  extend.\cb1 \
\
\cb5 Not: build the framework, then look for processes to run on it. That direction always ends with a beautiful runtime and no users.
