\f0\b0\fs31\fsmilli15750 \AppleTypeServices \cf4 \cb5 \strokec4 # Yes \'97 codecs is still the right starting place\cb1 \
\
\cb5 It's the smallest typed primitive every later layer needs. Building it first proves the type vocabulary and the assembly-time validation idea without any graph complexity. Everything after this (async, DSL, graph runtime, observability) sits on top of it without rewriting v1.\cb1 \
\
\cb5 ## The plan\cb1 \
\
\cb5 | Phase | Deliverable | Status |\cb1 \
\cb5 |-------|-------------|--------|\cb1 \
\cb5 | 1 | Sync codecs + linear pipeline + assembly-time type validation | 
\f2\b Done \'97 this MVP
\f0\b0  |\cb1 \
\cb5 | 2 | Async codecs (`JW3AsyncCodec` returning `JPromise`) for LLM + WebCrypto; stateful chunked codecs | Deferred |\cb1 \
\cb5 | 3 | JSON-DSL loader. Built against the first real LUW (after EDAM design pass) | Deferred |\cb1 \
\cb5 | 4 | Graph runtime: fan-out, conditional routing, error edges, retries, timeouts | Deferred |\cb1 \
\cb5 | 5 | Observability event bus (lifecycle events; tap node falls out of it) | Deferred |\cb1 \
\
\cb5 Each phase is additive. No v1 code gets rewritten.\cb1 \
\
\cb5 ## MVP delivered \'97 files in `/mnt/session/outputs/`\cb1 \
\
\cb5 ```\cb1 \
\cb5 helpers/JCodec.pas         Base class JW3Codec + TCodecType + ECodecError\cb1 \
\cb5 helpers/JCodecJSON.pas     JW3CodecJSON      ctJSON  \uc0\u8596  ctText\cb1 \
\cb5 helpers/JCodecBase64.pas   JW3CodecBase64    ctText  \uc0\u8596  ctText  (UTF-8 safe, browser + Node)\cb1 \
\cb5 helpers/JCodecHex.pas      JW3CodecHex       ctText  \uc0\u8596  ctText\cb1 \
\cb5 helpers/JPipeline.pas      JW3Pipeline       Fluent .Add() / .Encode / .Decode / .Validate / .Describe\cb1 \
\cb5 forms/FormCodecs.pas       TFormCodecs       Sidebar demo with 6 panes\cb1 \
\cb5 app.entrypoint.snippet.pas Lines to splice into your entry point\cb1 \
\cb5 README.md                  Plan, integration, roadmap\cb1 \
\cb5 NOTES.md                   My working notes (compiler quirks etc.)\cb1 \
\cb5 ```\cb1 \
\
\cb5 ## Key design calls I made (not negotiable, easy to revisit)\cb1 \
\
\cb5 - 
\f2\b Type vocabulary is four tokens:
\f0\b0  `ctText`, `ctBytes`, `ctJSON`, `ctAny`. Tiny on purpose. Richer types (`Lead`, `AuditFinding`, \'85) appear once the EDAM pass on a real process tells us what edges actually carry.\cb1 \
\cb5 - 
\f2\b Validation happens at construction.
\f0\b0  `JW3Pipeline.Validate` walks the chain checking `step[i].EncodeOutputType \uc0\u8596  step[i+1].EncodeInputType`. Returns a diagnostic string naming both offending codecs. `Encode`/`Decode` call this before any data flows.\cb1 \
\cb5 - 
\f2\b The pipeline owns its codecs.
\f0\b0  Freeing the pipeline frees the chain. Don't hand the same codec instance to two pipelines.\cb1 \
\cb5 - 
\f2\b Synchronous only.
\f0\b0  Async lives in a sibling class (phase 2). Mixing them in v1 was the kind of premature generality that always rots.\cb1 \
\cb5 - 
\f2\b Codec inherits the encode/decode duality from the dev-library framing.
\f0\b0  Each codec has Encode (always) and optional Decode. LLM nodes in phase 2 will be encode-only with `CanDecode = false`.\cb1 \
\
\cb5 ## Integration (5 minutes)\cb1 \
\
\cb5 1. Copy `helpers/J*.pas` \uc0\u8594  `ShoeStringV2/helpers/`\cb1 \
\cb5 2. Copy `forms/FormCodecs.pas` \uc0\u8594  `ShoeStringV2/forms/`\cb1 \
\cb5 3. In `ShoeStringV2/app.entrypoint.pas`, splice the three blocks from `app.entrypoint.snippet.pas`:\cb1 \
\cb5    - Add `JCodec, JCodecJSON, JCodecBase64, JCodecHex, JPipeline, FormCodecs` to `uses`\cb1 \
\cb5    - `Application.CreateForm('FormCodecs', TFormCodecs);`\cb1 \
\cb5    - `Application.GoToForm('FormCodecs');`\cb1 \
\cb5 4. Compile in Quartex Pascal IDE\cb1 \
\cb5 5. Open `ShoeStringV2/index.html`\cb1 \
\
\cb5 The sidebar gives you live JSON / Base64 / Hex / Pipeline round-trip / a deliberately-bad pipeline to see the type checker catch it / and a roadmap pane.\cb1 \
\
\cb5 The codec helpers are DOM-free \'97 they compile to a Node target unchanged. If you want a headless smoke test, point a Node entrypoint at the same units.\cb1 \
\
\cb5 ## Hand-off question\cb1 \
\
\cb5 I'd stop here and not build phase 2 yet. The next real forcing function isn't more framework \'97 it's a real LUW. Pick 
\f2\b one
\f0\b0  business process (my vote: Performance Audit, because it's bounded and the events are unambiguous) and run the EDAM pass on just that one. The output of that pass is the input to phase 3.\cb1 \
\
\cb5 So: 
\f2\b which process do you want to take through EDAM first \'97 Performance Audit, or something else?
